column3: Into the Blogosphere: Rhetoric, Community, and Culture of Weblogs: Blogging as Social Action: A Genre Analysis of the Weblog
column4: Paper by Carolyn R. Miller and Dawn Shepherd, North Carolina State University. "Why did blogging catch on so quickly and so widely? What motivates someone to begin and continue a weblog? What audience(s) do bloggers address? Who actually reads blogs and why? In short, what rhetorical work do blogs perform and for whom? And how do blogs perform this work? What features and elements make the weblog recognizable and functional? A genre analysis of the weblog will begin to answer these questions."

Roleplay in the Yukon gold rush days. Fuzzball 5.66. Roleplay logs, staff and character lists, policies, and a message board. Frames.
Anime and manga roleplay in a small modern Japanese city on an island. Rules, world guide, and application information.
Twisted Muck is a place where you can roleplay your favorite anime characters along with original characters you yourself create.
Furry fantasy-medieval roleplaying and social service. GlowMuck 3.1.7. History and race data, mailing list, and exhaustive information about the FurryFaire Role playing Program.
Fantasy roleplaying in a historical Asian country. ProtoMUCK 1.5. Theme and world history, rules, and character and application information.

column3: A Legend of Mana MUCK: Fa'Diel
column4: Roleplay in the world of Squaresoft's Legend of Mana RPG. Fuzzball 5.6. Original and feature character information, plots and logs, and roleplay and fighting rules.
Roleplay in the world of Squaresoft's Xenogears RPG. Fuzzball 5.6. Rules and application documents, roleplay logs, plot information, and message boards.
GlowMuck's new built-in commands, wizard levels, Multi-User Forth primitives, and help for other Glow-specific features such as the web server.
Help on building, Message Parsing Interpreter, description morphs, and hints and tips. Primarily for FurToonian "physics," but applies to most Fuzzball.

column3: Starting a MUCK: a short primer
column4: Quick technical guide to setting up a Fuzzball 5.x service.

column3: How to Connect to FurryMUCK (and elsewhere) - Rhal's Furry MU*s Page
column4: Basic, thorough help connecting to a server.
Roleplay in the future of the world of The Lion King.
Lion King roleplay. Fuzzball 5.6. Rules, application information, and player list with pictures.
Links to pages of Sociopolitical Ramifications members, includes pictures.
Political cartoons about FurrySpace.
Freeform roleplay on sci-fi worlds settled by the descendants of humanity, genetic recoms (furries) - Help files, character bios, and the encyclopedia of theme and world information
100% adult furry social service. Rules and online character application.
Furry social service. Fuzzball 5.6. Features policies, background, application information, event calendar, map, illustrated character pantheon, and community newsletter.
Light-hearted furry service, established 1995. Modified Fuzzball 5.6. Rules, staff list, online character request form, Graffiti Wall, and Java client.
Spartan furry service. Fuzzball 5.43. Policies, map, and request information.
Furry. Fuzzball 5.68. Staff list.
TinyMUCK 2.3. News, maps, and building information.
A social MUCK; with a theme of limited administration and rules, and maximum individual freedom. Site contains basic game information.
First furry MUD and the largest MUCK on the Internet. Fuzzball 5.6. Rules, online character request form, and general help. Frames.
MUD2 is the latest incarnation of the very first MUD (Essex MUD/MUD1/British Legends.)
Modern version of the original MUD created by Richard Bartle. Free with an online java client.
Includes an event summary and photographs.
The company behind MUD2 and the MUDDLE programming language and development system. Site includes telnet link to the original MUD1.
A MUSH where players and staff in the MU* community can meet to chat, promote their games, and share their ideas and knowledge.
Come roleplay North American Wild animals in a setting similar to Lion King or Watership Down.

Based on the roleplaying game of the same name by Holistic Design. A delightful combination of space opera and medieval fantasy, the Fading Suns Mush provides a rich setting for political and economic conflict.
Atlantis is an online roleplaying game centered around faction-based submarine warfare. It is a combination of science fiction and fantasy.
Although the game itself is now defunct, this site describes the MUSH world of Poddington-on-Slossip, a small village in Cornwall which, strangely, does not appear in any of Baedeker's guides.
Online gaming environment using Hero System 5th Edition rules. Unique, detailed game world. Interactive storylines and plots.
A historically themed roleplaying MUSH set in World War II.
A space-opera based MUSH with Hspace 5.0, numerous races, and friendly staff and players.

A supplementary source for the players of the TMNT MUSH, as well an information source for a MUSH-based Role Playing game based on the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles. Original and Cannon characters are welcomed and humans and mutants are adored!
An adventure in interactive roleplay based in the world of the X-Men that diverges from Marvel continuity circa August 1989.
The game is set in DC Comic's Gotham City just after the events of Batman: Fugitive. Players can create original or feature characters from DC titles.
An online internet adaptation of the role-playing game. Play as superheroes, supervillains, or game masters/admins.
A unique, strongly themed online text based role playing game that runs on a TinyMUSH 3 server.
A Harry Potter roleplaying MUSH that picked up the story after Goblet of Fire and continued from there. Features, ghosts, house elves, and adults available.
A high magick fantasy MUSH that allows both human and non-human characters.

An original-themed MUX with an emphasis on social RP and political intrigue, spiced up with a dash of swashbuckling derring-do. The setting is reminiscent of late 16th century France, with the addition of magic and other races.
Based on George R.R. Martin's fantasy epic 'A Song of Ice and Fire', Blood of Dragons MUSH is a role-playing game set 150 years prior to the books.
A gamed set in Sigil, City of Doors, from Dungeons and Dragons's Planescape setting.

column3: Rise From Chaos: a RIFTs MUX
column4: Based on Palladium's RIFTs, set in Tolkeen, a post-apocalyptic land struggling to maintain and defend the ragged principles of Freedom, Knowledge, and Virtue

column3: Harry Potter: A Snitch in Time
column4: A consent-based MUSH based on J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series of books. Both feature and original characters are accepted.
A tribe of elves attempts to survive on a new world, already occupied by other races, after theirs was destroyed.
A non-Earth late bronze/early Iron Age world with an ancient Greco-Roman feel. Offers a game information via wiki-style.
Site features game information, character directory, role-playing logs, FAQ section and updates page.
An online game based on Palladium's RIFTs, set in Kingsdale, an area rich in scenery, magic and role-playing possibilities.
Set in Tolkien's Middle Earth.

A Harry Potter themed text-based game set in the 1970s in the UK. They have friendly, competent staff, simple charged with approval, applications required only for features and special abilities, and a functional quidditch stat system.
Cuendillar MUSH is a role playing game set in an alternate weave of the world created by Robert Jordan in his Wheel of Time series.
A roleplaying MUSH based on the old Battlestar Galactica television series. Extensively coded systems, newbie friendly, and a well-established playerbase.
Features information on roleplaying, world and players.
A combination of superheroes, anime, science-fiction and other fun stuff in Hyper Metro City, a bridge between different worlds and times.
Heavy Gear RPG from Dream Pod 9 set in Khayr ad-Din, 'city of trash,' home to Rovers, renegades, mercenaries, Duelists and lowlives from all over Terra Nova.
Based on the Shadowrun system. Contains news, game overview, FAQ, and player pages.
A realtime, online futuristic mechanized war simulation.

Based on Anne McCaffery's Pern books. Set in the 10th Pass of the Red Star, which began in the last decade. Roleplaying is based on cooperation, rather than competition, so there is no system of points or combat.
An alternate timeline Pern MUSH centered around Southern Hold and Southern Weyr. The focus is on character-driven plots and interesting roleplay. Private game, characters by invitation only.
Constructive discussion, reminiscing, and occasional flamewars on issues relating to Pern-based MUSHes and MOOs.
Post-AIVAS Pern roleplaying in a long established MUSH with Weyrs, WeyrHolds, Holds and Crafts you may join.
Includes essays and links useful to those taking on or considering a goldrider position--or any leadership role on a Pern MUSH.
The official homepage of SouCon MUSH, an online game which celebrates Pern, the world of Anne McCaffrey, set in the Southern Continent.
A site for Kaylithin, dragonrider of blue Narith, for PernWorld Mush. Includes a portrait gallery, artwork, and images of sculptures.
Biographies and descriptions of the player's various characters since 1998.
Trista, Elydria, Lilla, and Wren of SouCon MUSH and Ilga and Zelez of PernMUSH.
Star Trek themed emphasising roleplay. Features combat, skills and economy.
Star Trek: Legacy is dedicated to keeping the legacy of Gene Roddenbury alive by creating a game where even novice non-Trekkers can learn how to interact appropriately in a Star Trek Universe.
2343 Before the Destruction of the Enterprise-C at Narenda III Space, the Final Frontier. Site offers news and basic game information.

First MUSH to appear with a Star Wars theme. It is a multi user roleplaying environment with a focus on roleplay and the interplay between characters and the groups in which they participate. It is set 4 years after the battle of Endor, and has fully coded Econ, Space and CharGen systems.
Fan site and information on Star Wars Galaxies. Provides information for players such as maps, races, and factions.

column3: Star Wars: Ways of the Force MUSH
column4: Set 5,000 years prior to episode 1. Features information on factions, planets, transport and combat.
Social MUX where one can hang out and make friends. A bit of warning though: people there may seem a little crazy at first, but new-comers get used to it.
Explorable areas and multiplayer attractions. Includes a space adventure, an ocean rpg, and a variety of player run areas. Free building is encouraged.
A virtual community which encourages diverse people all over the world to meet for discussions on different technical and personal topics.
DiscordiaMUSH is a relaxed social place to be.
M*U*S*H is an eclectic community of artists, experimenters, learners, and teachers.
A game with a partial World of Darkness setting and open character system.
Features chronicle background and character list for a Changeling MUSH set in Seattle, Washington.
The resource web site for Paris: Les Fleurs du Mal (The Flowers of Evil), a WOD game whose name was inspired by the works of the French poet Charles Baudelaire.
Garou-only mush. Very strict (some would say elitist) character creation policy.
World of Darkness themed game set in a futuristic New Orleans. Site provides detailed information about the game.
Cyberpunk themed game set in a post-apocalyptic Los Angeles. The site contains game information and a forum.
Old WOD-themed game set in fictional Crystal Springs, CO. Unifies most of the core games, and has a fairly strict character creation policy.
An Old World of Darkness MUX set in late 1990s Miami, supporting the Vampire, Hunter, and Werewolf settings.
The Reach is a World of Darkness MUX set in the fictional town of Aleswich, Maine. The game allows all templates save for Promethean.

A dark fantasy theme centered game, featuring vampires, werewolves and the undead, as well as their adversaries. Free to play, pay for perks. Contains news, game information and guides, forums, and support.
A dark and magical world. Features include the ability to govern cities and take power over villages villages. Free to play, but players can buy credits for certain advantages.

A world where the forces of magick war with those who oppose its use. Features an intense player combat, a wide range of tradeskills, and 14 classes. Roleplaying strongly encouraged. Free to play, but credits can be bought for certain advantages.
Official game site. Highly complex system with a built-in client. Free to play, but sells credits players can use to improve their characters.
A free to play, online RPG, based on the books written by Raymond Feist.
Launched in 1989, DragonMud is set in a magical and perpetually pre-industrial alternate London.
TCL/Tk client for Linux and Windows. Supports MCP.
Feature rich console client. Windows, Mac OS X, and Linux builds available.
GTK+ client with a built-in Perl interpreter. It runs under Windows and Linux.
Java client with most standard features. Windows and Linux builds available.
Open source client featuring Lua scripting. Windows and Linux builds available. In development.
GTK client with most standard features. Win32, OS X, and Linux builds available.
GTK client, with most standard features.
KDE client, with basic features and plugins. Allows Perl, Python and Ruby scripting.
Console client using the real telnet protocol. Allows triggers and scripting by perl, C, C++, and shell.
KDE client, with most standard features.
Tcl/Tk client with a console version. Provides Tcl based scripting and basic features.
Tk mush client written in perl.
Console client with most standard features.
Portable console client with most standard features. Has some MOO specific support.
GNOME client with most standard features. GNU General Public Licence.
Console client, with most standard features. Allows Perl and Python scripting.
Shareware client with most standard features.
Cocoa client with basic functionality. Offers Lua scripting.
Cocoa shareware client with most standard features. Offers perl scripting.
Windows client featuring an editor, MCP and TCL support, built-in MOO code parser, and an integrated list of MOO servers.

Windows and Unix client featuring ANSI, MacMOOSE and MCP 2.1 editor and user plug-in support. It is fully customizable and is an active development, which is open to ideas and contributions, with open sourcecode.
A port of MacMOOSE for Windows. Features MacMOOSE protocol support.
A unix/win/mac client geared toward MOO systems. Doesn't support ansi.
Linux client based on gtk+ supporting multiple worlds. It features MCP 2.1 support and includes a build in editor with syntax-highlighting and macro support.
Popular, feature-rich client. Commercial.
Console client with most standard features. Free.
Simple and compact client. Free/Proprietary.
Client with basic functionality.
Client with basic functionality. Free.
Client with most standard functionality and additional MU* features.
Client with most standard features and plugins. Free.
Client with most standard features. Free.
Commercial client with most standard features. Free.
Client with most standard features. Requires the .NET Framework.
Client with most standard features. Open Source.
Compact client with most standard features. Includes SSH. Based on PuTTY. Free.

Project to rewrite the Varium MUD server in Java, incorporating a Python interpreter for world development.
MUD server written in Java. The site contains news, related links, documentation, and the source code.
The Diabolically Uncrashable Mud Builder. Mud server implemented in Java consisting of a Lisp-like language interpreter for the creation of MUDs.
Java Universal Distributed Game Engine - based on a client/server architecture and written entirely in java.
Mud server written in Java boasting full telnet support, object property reflection, and a transparent storage management mechanism.
An open source, modular, extensible platform for building multi-user environment. Written in Java.
General purpose mud engine designed to be flexible. Site offers downloads and documentation.
Flexible mud engine using Groovy scriping. Site offers downloads and documentation.
The 'Diabolically Uncrashable MUD Builder' project aims to provide a server that is first and foremost stable and reliable. The DUMB language is a dialect of Lisp.
Graphical MUD system ported from AmigaMUD. Has a graphical MUD client written in Java and an efficient server written in C. CGMUD is not derived from any other MUD and has no licensing restrictions.
A group of programmers involved in developing in ColdC. ColdC is an object-oriented database language designed for setting up persistent online servers, such as MUDs.
Flexible open-source MUD engine, capable of supporting almost any role-playing setting.
A multi-player adventure game originally for the VMS. The site contains the original source code and a Linux port in C.

CoolMUD is an object-oriented, disk-based MUD server originally written by the creator of MOO. It has support for distributed processing. This version features some bug fixes in the server and improved in-database code.
Lars D?ning's modernized Amylaar LPMud gamedriver. Description of the driver, downloads.
A feature rich and actively maintained MudOS driver based on Nightmare.
The rec.games.mud.lp frequently asked questions list.
DGD is a generic multi-user server that can be used to create MUDs. Its behavior is completely defined by a programming language called LPC.
OpenTransport native RPG server with many MUD-like capabilities.
Modern Macintosh-hosted MUD server that features full support for classes, races, clans, ANSI color, HTML generation, moods, and languages.
Clients, Servers and general resources for mudders on Mac OS.
Annotated list of tutorials in MOO programming, intended for non-programmers.
Command-line and web-based tools to view information in MOO database files which are not executing.

Contains several useful MOO related items.
A collection of enhancements for the LambdaMOO server.

Mordor derived codebase. The site contains information on accessing the code repository.

A staff lister, object copier, and player information program.
Code archive, plus information on building, MUSH administration, TinyMUSH patches and hacks.
A small repository of softcoded global commands for PennMUSH games.

A popular TinyMUSH server with modern memory handling.
A version of PennMUSH compiled to work on Win32 systems.
Port of TinyMUSH to Macintosh.

Wiki containing information on running and playing a BattletechMUX.
A free, public starter database for TinyMUSH 3 based games.

Wiki site covering the four main MUSH codebases.
A small collection of utilities geared toward CyberPunk 2.0.2.0 players and admins.
A MUD server for Win32 written in Delphi 5. Features include multi-threaded design, copy-over procedure and IPv6 support.
Catalog of new and original MUD servers for different platforms and programming languages. Includes short descriptions and links to the project web pages and their authors.
Results and downloads of a competition to write the best possible MUD server in under 16 kilobytes.
List of popular mud servers with descriptions and links.
Large collection of snippets and codebases.

Offers MUD hosting packages on a high-speed connection.
Offers MUD and MOO accounts, MUD programming, web hosting, talker accounts, and FTP hosting.
Fast, reliable MUD hosting administered by MUDders for the benefit of MUDders.
Provides premium Linux-based mud, talker and web hosting services.
MUD hosting, source code and clients. Unix shells for eggdrops and iRCd. A MUD resource site by MU* designers.
Information about services and hosted MUDs.
MUD and talkers hosting services.
Various packages. Provides a mission statement, mud list and prices.
Includes information about the company and hosting plans.
Divine Right is an inexpensive web and MUD host that supports many codebases, including CoffeeMUD.
Mud hosting provider with dedicated support staff. Lots of features. Instant activation.
Offers offer MU* and traditional web hosting.
Offers paid MUD and traditional hosting.
Provides MU* hosting with no recurring fees.
Affordable MUD and MUSH hosting services. Provides professional game hosting solutions as well as guild hosting, web hosting and VPS servers.
Documentation of several protocols used for interMUD chat networks.
AberChat clients for both Diku and Aber MUDs.
SunNET is a hubless network for the LambdaMOO server. It provides a InterMUD protocol for MOO, with flexibility for programming possibilities.
A chat network based on the IMC2 protocol. Support forums, downloads, and a documentation of the IMC2 protocol.
A network utilizing MSDP for sending and retrieving chat messages.

Ratings, user counts, and an interface for user changes.
Collection of links to active MOO's, the list is sorted by category or alphabetically and includes a description. It also features a suggestion form for users to add to the directory.
MudVerse lists text-based games such as MUDs, MOOs, MUSHs and Browser based games.
Listing of MUDs that can be easily connected to using the build in flash client.
Offers reviews, articles, and two top 10 lists based on visitor votes and traffic.
Provides player count statistics and basic information for over a hundred MUDs.

Covers various topics including promotions, legal issues, and game design.
A forum dedicated to the discussion of MUD design.
Covers building, development, legal issues, MUD promotions and events.
Free speech haven which caters to the TinyMUD branch.

An aggregator seeded with a variety of MUD development related blogs.

Somewhat satirical wiki for TinyMUD related topics.
PBeM community resource.
Ladders for PBeM boardgames.
Offers news updates, mailing lists, and information on featured games including Eldritch, Iron Kings, and Monsters.
Articles and FAQs to help players and GMs. Topics include character development, how to write good posts and how to run a PBEM game.
The Internet version of the game show, hosted by Ryan and Doug Morris (No Relation)
Play a game with 1-6 other players via email on an arbitrarily sized board.
The mailing list necessary to play this nomic.
A space for collaborative maintenance of various documents related to the game of Nomic. The new home of the Nomic FAQ and then Net Nomic Database.
Defunct group. An archive of players, rulesets, proposals, and judgments.
Ranking page and strategy guide.

Richard's PBeM Server (pbmserv@gamerz.net) exists so that you can play a variety of games with players around the world by eMail. Among the 100+ games supported are: Chess, Checkers, Backgammon, and Othello.
Offers instructions and free board games, including chess, go, checkers, reversi, and tic tac toe, played through e-mail clients that support HTML.
Offers a variety of board games in various formats.
Includes information and files for completed and open games.
Organizes various games. Site contains information on the games offered, and how to join.
Correspondence gaming community. Offers the organization of Chess, Backgammon, Checkers, Reversi, Xianqui, Link4, Ataxx, Chinese Checkers, Twixt, Go, Zertz and other games.
Greg Lindahl's game list.

column3: La Cosa Nostra PBeM Mafia Sim
column4: The plot is as thus, you are the leader of an organized crime syndicate, vying for control of first a small area in a city, and eventually the whole city!
Fun simulation of what it is like to own and care for a horse. Updated regularly.
A project whose goal is to provide easy to use tools for creating and running play by e-mail games.
Information on designing and writing computer PBM games.

column3: Trivia of the Day Game Homepage
column4: A play by email daily trivia game. Played Monday thru Friday with a question each morning and the previous day's answer. Winners are ranked at the end of the month.
Interesting and informative trivia questions e-mailed to you every week.
Several general knowledge quizzes with a Smart Chart system to keep track of your points to compare with the world.
Riddles, trivia, illusions, puzzles, and brain teasers.
Riddles, trivia, and humor articles.

column3: Dark Neon Flashback: Back To The Eighties
column4: Exclusive original interviews with the pop stars of the 80s, plus fact files, trivia and links on site and via newsletter.
Competitive league, with descriptions of Trivial Pursuit editions.
Information on Disney Animation plus free Daily Disney Email List.
Publishes Trivia of the Day: A daily newsletter with a new piece of Trivia each day. New trivia will appear on the web page about a week after they have been in the newsletter.
Role playing game, strictly wild horses.
A horse sim where you can act as wild horses might. This game is suitable for children of all ages. One of few sites going for complete realism.
Interactive horse roleplaying game; create a herd, challenge and fight for mares, foals, and land. A fun game for ages 12 to adult.
A light/dark/neutral wild horse RPG, aimed mainly at intermediate-advanced players. Message board based. Includes a constantly evolving plot and open positions/lands.
COMPLETELY wild horse RPG. No talking is allowed. Intermediate to advanced players please.
Become a part of this pack of loup-garou(werewolves) and find a place among those like you.
A wolf and multi-species game set in a diverse landscape, with the opportunity to play as mythical creatures as well.
A forum based role play for real wolves. No fantasy but real life wolves in the Canadian forests. Accepting all members. Looking for experienced role players but willing to teach.

column3: Lost In Mists - Unlock the Wolf WIthin!
column4: A wolf roleplay focused around gaining Powers from mythical Sprytes, with and interesting plotline and plenty of open positions.
Fictional, forum-based, play-by-post roleplaying game focused on creative writing, character development, and interaction between members.
Game in which the player roleplays the life of a sailor.
Online role playing forum with multiple aspects of game play.
Chat based roleplaying set in a high school in New York. Players define their characters grade, sports and other activities and family background.
Allows you to join as a Dragon Ball, Starcraft, Final Fantasy, or Sailor Moon member. IRC based.
Elven based roleplay spread across a number of linked channels, providing a large environment. Articles on Elven life and information on joining. Over 18 ONLY.
A freeform roleplay wolf pack on SorceryNet. Site has pack information as well as information on the wild wolf, support and artwork and writings by players.
A FFRPG set on a luxury cruise ship and the various ports it docks in. Information on setting and characters details, along with referenced logs.
Highly detailed website giving much information on this FFRP channel on the Chattacomb network. Also artwork and stories based on the game.
An empire-style freeform RPG whose society is based on torture and BDSM. 18+ recommended. Site gives play guidelines, character profiles and in-character information.

Archives from research in analysis, separation, synthesis, biosynthesis, analogues, derivatives, isotopes, radiated modifications, glycosylation, polyamines and peptides, Applications in medicine, food chemistry, nutrition, pharmacology, and roles in pathophysiology from Springer.

Italian biotechnological company focused on the discovery, development and marketing of new and innovative diagnostic products and on recombinant protein production under research grade, GLP and GMP conditions.

Collaboration of ten multi-disciplinary research centers, to develop technologies, and apply them to advancing knowledge of heart, lung, blood, and sleep health and disease. Includes links to participants throughout the USA.
Article outlining methods and technologies involved, use of biomarkers in clinical conditions, and emerging branches of study, with bibliographic references.
This search engine is formulated to search databases for specific data pertaining to genomes and proteomes of living organisms.

Provides glossary, career opportunities, education, scientific posters, seminars and meeting reviews. Includes discussion board for panel discussions, a public forum and worldwide networking from Ross, CA.
APS promotes proteomics research in Australia and New Zealand.

SEProt was born with the objective of encouraging the development of Proteomics in Spain, grouping together researchers in the field of Proteomics, users of Proteomics Services, private companies in the sector, and students interested in the study of proteomes.
Greek Society for Proteomics

Established to coordinate, integrate, strengthen and promote fundamental research, education, training and applications throughout Europe.

Resource for human plasma proteins along with their isoforms, specific expression, disease, localization, post translational modification and SNP. Includes FAQ, query interface, or browsing by structure or function.

resource maintained by the Ludwig Institute for Cancer Research, Academy of Cancer Immunology and European Cancer Immunome Program. [requires free registration]

column3: Orientations of Proteins in Membranes Database
column4: OPM of transmembrane, monotopic, peripheral polypeptides and their spatial arrangement in situ of PDB entries. Includes classification, 3D imagesand contacts at the University of Michigan, Ann Arbor.

Assembles all existing ciliary and basal body proteomics data into an open resource for the scientific community with the ultimate aim of exploring further the role of the cilium in disease and the mechanisms underlying ciliary biology.

Searchable database with references.

Commercial resources for research and protein expression profiling.

The ACS's Journal of Proteomic Research investigates the rapidly changing arena of proteomic research.

The translational nature of this technology provides unique challenges and unbounded opportunities that promise to transform the way disease is detected, treated, and managed.

The journal publishes review articles in all aspects of the fast-expanding field of proteomics. All areas of proteomics are covered together with the methodology, software, databases, technological advances and applications of proteomics, including functional proteomics.

column3: OMICS A Journal of Integrative Biology
column4: The Journal explores advances in the era of post-genomic biology and medicine, including pharmacogenomics, and physiomics. Integrative, quantitative, experimental, and computational approaches bring new knowledge, novel methods, and innovative technologies to engender a better understanding of complex biological systems and processes.

Access to the online submission and editorial system for the official journal of the European Proteomics Association (EuPA). Includes links to guidance to authors and articles dating back to the Journal of Biochemical and Biophysical Methods.

Provider of services for protein biomarker discovery, assay development and testing. In Ann Arbor, Michigan, USA and Letchworth Garden City, Hertfordshire, UK.
Developing a new technology platform that can shorten the time-to-market for the commercialization of protein therapeutics. Based in Boston, Massachusetts, USA.

Offers consulting in project design, projects for drug target, marker discovery, protein inventory and mode of action studies. Also data evaluation service, training in 2D gel and mass spectrometry analysis from Berlin, Germany.
Develops algorithmic based pattern recognition technologies as predictors for analyzing proteomic data. Profile of expertise and company in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.

ProteoSep gel-free technology using LC-MS and other characterization techniques, for mapping intact proteins retained in the liquid phase for subsequent post translational modifications. Based in Darien, Illinois.

Company inviting collaboration with biopharmaceutical companies on selected proteins, for mapping interactions, validating targets for drug screening for cancer, infectious and metabolic diseases, in Paris, France.

Offers various proteomics products and services including protein identification, protein and peptide characterization, C18 nano columns, custom-packed nano columns.

Developing protein biomarker screen in human tissues, for clinical applications, using integrated multidimensional capillary, microfluidics and bioinformatics technologies. Overview of systems and company in Rockville, Maryland.

Includes sale of coated CE capillaries, protein arrays from tumors, cation exchange peptide standard columns, and buffers from Morgantown, West Virginia.

Offering specialist trypsin and custom peptide libraries to isolate, detect, identify and characterize protein structure and function, for both native and recombinant protein analysis, including glycoproteins and tools for glycobiology.

Portfolio of tools for cell-free expression, cell-based transfection, protein purification, processing, characterization and analysis of pathways.

Offers protein microarrays in a multiplex ELISA format, custom array development and validation and a sample testing service.

Offer identification and validation of drug targets and bio-markers, using mass spectrometric analysis, including MALDI-MS PMF, nanoLC-ESI-MS/MS and bioinformatics from Berlin, Germany.

Facility for the research community, with instrumens, protocols, educational materials and message boards. Includes links to services and project feasibility submission at Michigan State University, East Lansing.

Resource center for research and development in Lund, Sweden.

column3: Statistical Applications in Genetics and Molecular Biology

Quarterly publication with full text, including protocols and illustrations back to 1996. Provided by the International Society for Plant Molecular Biology.

Publishes articles on teaching techniques and practice in biochemistry and molecular biology. Includes aims and scope, contents, archives from 2005, instructions for authors and subscription information.

Has presented current research in environmental, adaptational, and comparative physiology and biochemistry since 1928. Original research results represent a variety of areas, including thermoregulation, respiration, circulation, osmotic and ionic regulation, environmental acclimation, evolutionary physiology, and metabolic physiology and biochemistry.

column3: Critical Reviews in Biochemistry and Molecular Biology
column4: Published bimonthly providing review articles on recent advances in the field of biochemical and molecular biology. Includes details of aims and scope, instructions for authors, the latest issue and forthcoming articles.

column3: Journal of Cell and Molecular Biology
column4: International journal which covers original research works in the field of cell biology, molecular biology, genetics, microbiology, neurobiology, bioinformatics and related topics.

Publishes original research and review articles reporting new developments in the genetics, molecular biology and biochemistry of prokaryotic and eukaryotic microorganisms, and covers the most important advances in bacterial pathogenicity.

column3: Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology Part B Biochemistry and Molecular Biology
column4: This journal covers biochemical and molecular biology aspects of metabolism, enzymology, regulation, nutrition, signal transduction, promoters, gene structure and regulation, metabolite and cell constituents, macromolecular structures, adaptational mechanisms and evolutionary principles.
ScienceDirect is the webserver of Elsevier Science with access to fulltext articles of journals for subscribers to this service
Subset of a searchable index, with links maintained by list by Genamics.
Lists academic journals in this field. Provides descriptions to help research scientists make decisions on the best journal for the submission of manuscripts and for research.
Magazine of the Biochemical Society, containing features, news, events, announcements, book reviews and company information
Presents research highlights from the best research produced by the Asia-Pacific International Molecular Biology Network.
Online magazine and community for molecular and cell biology researchers. Provides daily tech tips and news articles on advances in molecular and cell biology.
Major research center coordinating molecular biology research. Includes sites in Grenoble, Hamburg, Heidelberg, Hinxton, and Monterotondo.

column3: Centre for Molecular Medicine and Therapeutics
column4: The CMMT is a site for research on the determination and control of genetic susceptibility to disease. Lists core facilities, laboratories, staff and news from Vancouver, British Columbia.

column3: Laboratory for Advanced Biotechnology and Biomedical Micro-instrumentation
column4: Research group working on lab-on-a-chip, biochip, and single DNA manipulation at Pohang University of Science and Technology, South Korea.
Staff, publications and research on bacteria, parasites, viruses and vectors involved in infectious disease, at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, UK.
Research into cell signaling, proteomics, cellular simulation, microbiology, and development bioscience software at Pacific Northwest National Laboratory.
Information from the Polish Academy of Sciences on the Institute, its online journals, biological databases and other activities.

column3: University of Fribourg: Unit of Biochemistry
column4: Provides details of the research being undertaken and the people involved in several labs at the University of Fribourg in Switzerland.

The Respiratory Epithelium and Pulmonary Surfactant Investigation Group at the Universidad Complutense, Madrid. Main research areas are membrane biochemistry and biophysics, structure/function relationships in surfactant proteins and the role of pulmonary surfactant in lung physiopathology.

column3: The Ahern Lab: University of British Colombia
column4: Research is focused on voltage-gated sodium channels as regulators of excitability in nervous and muscle tissue. Also includes publications, people and a lab blog.
Undertakes fundamental research into the structure, regulation and maintenance of the genetic material in various organisms ranging from Escherichia coli and Saccharomyces cerevisiae to human cells.
Aims to characterize the structure/function relationships of a variety of enzymatic catalysts at the atomic level. At the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center in Seattle, Washington.
Provides an overview of the department and information on the faculty.

column3: University of California, San Francisco: Department of Bioengineering and Therapeutic Sciences
column4: Research in Dr. Kathleen Giacomini's lab focuses on the roles of membrane transporters in drug absorption, disposition, targeting and in clinical drug response.

Research at EMBL emphasises experimental analysis at multiple levels of biological organization, from the molecule to the organism, as well as computational biology, functional genomics and systems biology.

Offers script-driven programming for data analysis in viral dynamics, enzyme kinetics, receptor binding and drug discovery screening. Includes demo download, technical support and contacts for consulting in Pullman, Washington.

Package for statistical analysis of steady-state enzyme kinetic data, and presentation graphics, for Macintosh or Windows based computers. Previews, price and form to order from Princeton, New Jersey.
Offering predictive software tools and services for metabolic engineering and drug discovery. Based in Germany.
Links to biological software for DNA sequencing, molecule modeling, polymerase chain reaction and taxonomy.
Free MacOS X program for molecular biologists that can be used to determine which restriction enzymes cut a DNA sequence. Includes list of all commercially available RE.
Free DNA sequencing chromatogram trace viewer. Runs on Window, MacOS X, Linux and Solaris. Uses QT library.
Offers the Gensearch software to locate and analyse potential mutation locations.
Java based commercial software for DNA and Protein sequence analysis. Demo available.
Offers software for sequence alignment, phylogenetic tree visualization, contig assembly and sequence proof reading
Free MacOS X programs for molecular biologists. Offers 4Peaks - a DNA sequencing trace viewer, iRNAi - RNAi design, and LabAssistant - lab timer/organizer.
Java based biologist's workbench by Luca I.G.Toldo.
Software developed by the Broad Institute for visualizing and manually annotating whole genomes. Free for research and educational users
software to improve the quality of DNA sequencing traces collected on the ABI 3700 and 3730 DNA sequencers.
Macintosh software which provide sequence editing, primer design, database searching, protein analysis, alignment, phylogeny, and other functions.

StarBiochem is an application that displays molecules from the Protein Data Bank. It allows users to explore fundamental biological research concepts, select parts of the molecule and control how the selected parts are displayed.
A new base caller for ABI DNA sequencers including the 377, 3700, 310, 3100, 3130 and 3730 models. Provides increases in read length of 20 to 100%.
Analysis software and service for 2D electrophoresis gels as tools for multivariate statistical analysis.

Develops data management software solutions for life sciences research. Products include tools for genomics, proteomics, biorepositories, multiple laboratories, systems biology and translational research.
Provides details of a number of molecular biology tools, some of which are freeware.

column3: The International Society for Computational Biology
column4: The International Society for Computational Biology is dedicated to advancing the scientific understanding of living systems through computation; the emphasis is on the role of computing and informatics in advancing molecular biology.
EMBnet is the only organisation world-wide bringing bioinformatics professionals to work together to serve the expanding fields of genetics and molecular biology.

column3: Society for Bioinformatics in the Nordic Countries
column4: SocBiN is a non-profit organisation for people working with and interested in bioinformatics. One task of the society is to arrange annual conferences on Bioinformatics.
Easy-to-use summary of genomic information currently available for all organisms-from the Technical Univ. of Denmark.
A bioinformatics site, with access to multiple database searching and sequence analysis tools - from the Weizmann Institute of Science.

Information from Wikipedia on this branch of biology which involves the use or development of techniques, including applied mathematics, informatics, statistics, computer science, artificial intelligence, chemistry, and biochemistry to solve biological problems, usually on the molecular level.
Editable by the whole bioinformatics community, OpenWetWare provides bioinformatics tutorials and reviews that are kept up-to-date by the readers themselves.

Aims to develop the bioinformatics network infrastructure, encourage the exchange of data and information, develop training programs, workshops and symposia and encourage collaborations in the field of bioinformatics.
A resource site on bioinformatics, its history, scope, literature, databases, analytical tools and job openings.
Compendium of bioinformatics computing services from The Rockefeller University. Many different ways to analyse biomolecules.
Links to online genomics resources - including the individual projects.
Curated list of sequence search utilities, as well as databases and tools related with proteomics and structural bioscience.
Contains resources on Bioinformatics classified by categories.
A compendium of tools for molecular biology, biotechnology, molecular evolution, biochemistry and biomolecular modeling.
Features curated links to molecular resources, tools and databases.
Bioinformatics portal which integrates protein information, databases and research tools for researchers and students. Subscription based service.
Students raise chicken embryos in the classroom and obtain magnetic resonance images through the Internet.
Graduate program at Iowa State University offering Undergraduate Major (BCBio) and the PhD program (BCB).
Provides navigation to C. elegans/mammalian Bioinformatics, aging, oxidative stress (Channel 1); 1-2 new recent abstracts featured/week (Channel 2); Technology highlights (Channel 3).
Maintained by Dr. Seyeon Weon, Korea providing information on courses, a database archive, software archive and online resources.
This is a bioinformatics site created by undergrads primarily for undergrads. It has instructions and links for bioinformatic tools and resources.

Research based interdisciplinary training of graduate students in computational molecular biology with emphasis on bioinformatics, genomics, genome evolution, and macromolecular structure-function studies at Iowa State University.
Bioinformatics course at Yale University. All course slides are available online.
Interdisciplinary PhD and Masters Programs that include an internship in the local industry companies. In conjunction with the NE masters program.
Information about several medically important genes and related diseases. Illustrates the use of bioinformatics in their study.
Bioinformatics group for students interested and/or working in the bioinformatics/computational biology fields. Offers opportunities to exchanging information and sharing ideas.
Singapore Bioinformatics conducting informatics research, development, and training, to generate knowledge from large volumes of Biology and Chemistry data

column3: Masters in Bioinformatics at Glasgow University
column4: One-year Masters degree in Bioinformatics, consisting biological and computational strands followed by 15-week research project. Located in Scotland
Information on the student training opportunities offered by the CIHR/Michael Smith Foundation in Bioinformatics.
Provides onsite training on specific bioinformatics databases and tools. Also offers bioinformatic software testing and research consulting services.

column3: The Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics Homepage (SIB)
column4: SIB operates the ExPASy proteomics server and the Swiss node of EMBnet. Teaching activities include a series of post-graduate courses given at the Universities of Geneva and Lausanne, as well as at the EPFL, and a Masters Degree in bioinformatics. Major research areas include the development of integrated databases and software resources in the field of proteomics.
Provides online courses in Perl programming for bioinformatic tools.
From the Biology department and in cooperation with Boston University. Emphasis on the ability to integrate knowledge from biological, computational, and mathematical disciplines.
A two year Masters Degree Programme in Bioinformatics (MBI) offered by the University of Helsinki and Helsinki University of Technology, Finland.
Instructional materials for teaching bioinformatics. These include animated tutorials on topics such as BLAST, finding mutations in a protein, and graphing with MS-Excel.
Forum featuring various aspects, events and developments in the bioinformatics field.
Blog focusing on bioinformatics, biotechnology, pharma regulatory affairs, IPR and clinical trials.
A one-year, international master's programme in bioinformatics at the University of Skovde, Sweden.
An international, two-year Master's programme jointly managed by the University of Tampere and the University of Turku, Finland.
A two year, international master's programme in bioinformatics at the Universita di Bologna, Italy.
The University of British Colombia Bioinformatics Centre offers M.Sc. and Ph.D. degrees to students doing research in the field of bioinformatics.

column3: North Dakota State University: Genomics and Bioinformatics
column4: Graduate program and application information.

column3: Bioinformatics and Computational Biology at ISU
column4: An Interdisciplinary Graduate Program offering Ph.D. and M.S. degrees in Bioinformatics and Computational Biology (BCB) at Iowa State University
A bioinformatics group created by students, for students. Helps to educate other undergrads about bioinformatics and the tools available online.

column3: Index of Computational Molecular Biology and Bioinformatics Courses
column4: Listing of computational molecular biology course pages that have extensive online course materials.
The home page of the computational Biology course at Stony Brook.
A list of on-line course materials and tutorials for bioinformatics and computational biology.
Summary of basics of bioinformatics for the intelligent newcomer.
Website presents a series of lectures on bioinformatics and modern drug research at the University of Konstanz.
Specializing in making publicly available software and database services for computational biology.
Course materials, book recommendations and links related to bioinformatics.

column3: Protein sequence analysis: A practical guide
column4: A web-based tutorial associated with "Introduction to bioinformatics" published by Addison Wesley Longman.
Offers short courses in bioinformatics, genomics and proteomics in various cities across Canada.
Worldwide job offers in bioinformatics.
Features job postings, discussion groups, resumes and career resources.

column3: Systolic Accelerator for Molecular Biological Applications (SAMBA)
column4: Processor array for speeding comparison of biological sequences using a parameterized version of the rigorous Smith-Waterman algorithm - from the IRISA, Rennes FR.
A hardware base DNA sequencing trace reprocessing system for improving the read length and throughput of the ABI 3100, 3130 and 3730 DNA sequencers.
Tools and methods for computational biology. Working on secondary protein structure prediction, providing reliable profiles, and developing new ways to study molecular biology through bioinformatics.
Retrieves molecular biology data and bibliographic citations from the NCBI's integrated databases.
GeneBio provides proteomics software tools and databases including SWISS-PROT, PROSITE, SWISS-2DPAGE and Melanie. We also offer a secure version of ExPASy molecular biology web server.

column3: INCBI Irish National Centre for BioInformatics
column4: Hosts Irish embnet node, Gives links to Database browsing and interrogation at SRS, European (EBI) servers, Blast server for parasite genomes (EBI), US (NCBI) servers, Protein structure prediction, PredictProtein Server in Heidelberg, Gene identification, splice sites, exons, introns and a list of gene structure prediction programs
Text and similarity searching, provided by the National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).

column3: Molecular Informatics Resource for the Analysis of Gene Expression
column4: Information methodologies, tools, and technologies relating to the study of gene expression and signal transduction from the Institute for Transcriptional Informatics.

column3: Center Structural Biology: Programs and Tools
column4: User guides and worked examples for software applications in structural and molecular biology - from Yale Univ.
BIND is a database designed to store full descriptions of interactions, molecular complexes and pathways.
MINT is a database designed to store functional interactions between biological molecules (proteins, RNA, DNA).
Several genomics and proteomics tools, including multiple alignments, gene expression analysis, tandem repeat and motif discovery.
Finds novel transcription factor binding sites by searching for over-represented (most significant motifs) motifs in DNA sequences.

The focus of the GBF project "Molecular Bioinformatics of Gene Regulation" are regulatory genomic signals and regions that govern transcriptional control based on TRANSFAC - The Transcription Factor Database. It compiles data about gene regulatory DNA sequences and protein factors binding to and acting through them.

Performs single-coverage local multiple DNA sequence alignments of finished and draft-quality genome sequences. It also provides with an option to predict transcription factor binding sites evolutionarily conserved across multiple species.
Service using the ParAlign algorithm to compare genetic sequences. Apparently it is as fast as BLAST and as sensitive as Smith-Waterman.
Open web platform for modeling and reverse engineering of photosynthetic dynamism.
Online service integrating biological data from genomics, biochemistry, genetics and high-throughput expression profiling, to achieve a pattern-based analysis of genes and genomes.
A free software tool for analysing the hypothetical secondary structure of a family of homologous RNA.
An online service for periodically performing predefined searches at NCBI, reporting new results by email or on the web.
Online program that calculates the distribution of offspring genotypes from dominant, codominant and recessive gene crosses, for up to 6 genes.
Uses the network of genes and proteins as a natural way of accessing the millions of biomedical abstracts in PubMed.

A database of sequence comparisons between all publicly available prokaryotic genome sequences, allowing the on-line visualisation of comparisons between up to five genomic sequences, using the Artemis Comparison Tool. User can perform their comparisons on their own data.

Resource for storing, searching and retrieving published mathematical models of biological interests. Models present in BioModels Database are annotated and linked to relevant data resources, such as publications, databases of compounds and pathways, controlled vocabularies, etc.
Offers more than 30 online services for DNA and protein bioinformatics analysis.
Protein ANnotation Diagram ORiented Analysis service that extracts biological information from user supplied sequences.
MGRC provides contract genomes services, sequencing services, data and access services.
Online services including T-Coffee, El-Nemo, Casper and FeeBack.
LGICdb is a curated repository of genes coding for subunits of Ligand-Gated Ion Channels.
Service for the identification of bacteria and fungi sequences by sequence alignment.
Database of genetic and physical interactions. It contains interaction data from many sources, including several genome/proteome-wide studies, the MIPS database, and BIND.

A commercial service for improving the read length and quality of ABI 3730, 3130 and 3100 DNA sequencing traces. Works via reprocessing of the raw peak data before re-base calling. A free trial is provided.
Helps users design zinc finger transcription factors.
Suite of user-friendly tools that evaluate the impact of gene splicing variation on specific molecular biology techniques.
Tool for querying Evidence Viewer Database (EVDB), a comprehensive, non-redundant collection of splice variant data for human genes.
Provides a complete set of bioinformatics tools and public databanks updated daily, and a range of links to seminars, training courses and platform news.
Framework and web portal specifically designed for the integration of bioinformatics software and databanks. Provides a tutorial and an interactive guided tour.

A free web-based Laboratory Information Management System (LIMS), aimed at a typical small molecular biology laboratory allowing members to have their own private forum, events, Electronic Lab Notebook (ELN) and a LIMS area.
DBD is a database of predicted transcription factors in completely sequenced genomes. The predicted transcription factors all contain assignments to sequence specific DNA-binding domain families.
Provides an internet service that calculates the site, geometry and energy of small molecules interacting with proteins.

This platform provides over 100 methods for the analysis and visualization of gene expression, copy number, proteomic and other data. It enables biologists to add new analyses and create workflows that can be shared, edited and published.
A suite of tools for the analysis of sRNA datasets from high-throughput sequencing experiments.
An integrated software system for storing, managing, analyzing, and querying metabolic pathways at genetic, molecular, biochemical and organism levels.
Converts gp files from NCBI GenPept format to fasta. Its main purpose is to create fasta files with short, but still accurate headers for sequence.
Provides a collection of information on data sources for biological networks, file formats that save biological networks and software to analyze the information of these sources.
Scientists at the Broad Institute have developed a range of software tools for the analysis of increasingly large genome-related datasets. These are openly available to the scientific community.
The PubMed search system provides access to the MEDLINE and PREMEDLINE databases.
Web application that searches gene symbols or MeSH terms and displays resulting pairs of genes and MeSH terms that match the search term.
Web application that searches biological substances or MeSH terms and displays resulting pairs of substances and MeSH terms that match the search term.

MiMi Web provides an interface to a NCIBI data repository for conducting systems biology analyses. This repository includes the MiMI database, PubMed resources updated nightly, and text mined from biomedical research sources.
Scans sequences for potential transcription factor binding sites using JASPAR and TRANSFAC.
A suite of online tools for analysis of DNA/RNA, proteins and arrays.
Consolidates evidence for gene-gene interactions from HPRD, BIND, Reactome, KEGG, GO, microarray co-expression and Y2H experiments.
Online version of the program for populational genetics.
Tools for comparing, exploring and visualizing correlated genes in two microarray experiments in yeast transcriptomes. Includes visualization of induced gene groups based on MIPS catalogues.

Tools for managing, accessing, and analyzing cDNA microarray data generated by the NCI Div. of Clinical Sciences ?Array Center - from the BioInformatics and Molecular Analysis Section of the NIH Center for Info. Technology.
Portal to protein subcellular localization resources and tools, for prediction in gram negative bacteria. Maintained by the Brinkman Laboratory, Simon Fraser University, BC, Canada.
Identification of gene features such as exons and splice sites in genomic DNA.
Prediction of locations and exon-intron structures in genomic sequences, incorporating protein homology information when predicting genes from DNA sequence. Webserver at the MIT.
Search engine that uses mass spectrometry peptide data to identify proteins from primary sequence databases.
Provides a tool for statistical analysis and visualization of high-throughput biological data using gene ontology.
Generates information on composition and distribution of putative Quadruplex forming G-Rich Sequences (QGRS) in nucleotide sequences and NCBI genes.
Contains rat genomic data such as genes, SSLPs, ESTs, QTLs, and strain information and tools such as vcmap, genome scanner, rhmap server, metagene. Also has a rat research community forum.
This site contains information on mouse genetic markers, mapping, phenotypes, mammalian homology and gene expression. All data are searchable through a set of Query Forms.
A fully-searchable database to provide information and easy access to over 200 current and completed genome projects.
Provides direct access to the data computed on several organisms such as Rat, Mouse, Drosophila, and Bovine as it relates to human genome sequencing.
A collection of databases and tools designed to help researchers understand the genetics of human ageing.

column3: Gramene: A comparative genomic resource for grains
column4: Gramene is a curated, open-source data resource that provides agricultural researchers and plant breeders with biological and genomic information on rice and other grasses.

Integrated clade oriented genome database for the Solanaceae (tomato, potato, pepper, eggplant etc.) and other Asterids. Contains genetic maps, gene sequences, phenotypic descriptions and images, tomato genome sequence and gene annotations.
An integrated database of genomic, expression and protein data for Drosophila and Anopheles.
DNA microarray gene annotation database.
A transcriptome-wide atlas database for the developing mouse embryo established by RNA in situ hybridization.

Resource for genomic information on yeast, with tutorial on gene ontology, homology searches and comparisons. Includes links to tools, related conferences, and staff at Stanford University School of Medicine, California.
MaizeGDB is the community database for biological information about the crop plant Zea mays.
Website for S. erythraea NRRL23338 genome sequencing project.
An interactive genome browser supporting multiple species. X:Map displays mapping between Affymetrix Exon Arrays and their corresponding genes and exons.
A tool for scientists and researchers. Provides views for a variety of genomes, complete chromosomes, sequence maps with contigs, and integrated genetic and physical maps.
PhenomicDB is a multi-organism phenotype/genotype database. Users can compare the phenotypes of a gene over many organisms simultaneously.

column3: Other Species Genome Databases and Servers
column4: A useful list of resources.
Portal accessing third-party sources of gene expression, function and structure, for user-personalized reporting. Maintained by Genomics Institute of the Novartis Research Foundation.
Resource formed by individuals and institutions for development of knockout rats using different technologies. Includes classification, applications, FAQ, forum and member login.
Offers analysis of protein sequence sets from individual sequences to complete genomes.
Sensitive, selective, and rapid sequence database searching with gapped alignments - from Washington Univ.-St.Louis.
Access to Smith-Waterman-based FDF sequence comparison program, with excellent explanation of when to use it vs. BLAST - from the Univ. of Lausanne, FR.
Detection and assessment of similarity between distantly related sequences by means of a variety of remotely-executable software - from the Swiss Inst. for Experimental Cancer Research.

column3: HMM library for all proteins of known structure
column4: This is a server for structural superfamily assignments to protein sequences using Hidden Markov Models. The services included are: -homology searching -alignments -genome assignments
Implementation of hidden Markov models for sequence analysis. Free UNIX software for nonprofit groups, and sequences can be submitted online.
Utility for online manipulation of Blast results. Results organized in a table format.
Open source tool for identifying serial repeats (tandem repeats) in DNA sequences.
Formatting of multiple sequence alignments to a color postscript file. Can include graphical features by using PDB entry.

Suite of alignment tools to detect conserved sequences, similar domain architecture, gene expression profiles, and SNP using protein or nucleotide targets. Includes support and archiving of strategies at NCBI, Bethesda, Maryland.
Provides a map of restriction enzyme sites and a list of non-cutting enzymes for a corresponding DNA sequence.
The restriction enzyme database. Maintained by the New England Biolabs, USA.
Provides restriction analysis, silent mutation scanning and SNP-RFLP analysis. Allows for utilization of all commercially available type II restriction enzymes.
Finds restriction enzyme cleavage sites in linear and circular DNA sequences. Provides also a virtual digest function.
Generates primers for Ligation Independent Cloning (LIC).
Displays the codon quality in two different ways, codon usage frequency or relative adaptiveness values. FAQ included.
Offers server generated plasmid maps and image files, from input DNA sequences up to 20,000 bp. Includes citation, and dowloadable source code. Maintained by the University of Alberta, USA.
Analyses up to three trace files collected on the ABI 3730 and 3730xl DNA sequencers.
Provides a DNA sequence analysis to find restriction enzymes sites. Finds also non-overlapping open reading frames using the E.coli genetic code.
Converts amino acid and nucleotide sequence data formats including FASTA, GenBank, Phylip and others. Maintained by NIH, USA.
Provides reverse complement sequence for DNA or RNA primer strands, self complementarity check, physical and thermodynamic constants, melting temperature (Tm). Includes calculation formulas.
Translates a plane format of the DNA sequence (first ORF only) to amino acid sequence. Provides numbering of every 10th AA and every 30th bp and align them by codon.
Provides primers specific to the PCR template sequence. Includes primer pair specificity checking against a selected database.
A Java application that facilitates the identification of potential ORFs, based on provided DNA sequence and probable ORF length.

Identifies all ORFs using the standard or alternative genetic codes. Provides an interactive, graphical interface and allow for saving of a deduced amino acid sequence in various formats. Allows searching against the sequence database using the BLAST server.
Provides restriction enzyme digest analysis of the input DNA sequence. Results are presented graphically as a "virtual gel".
DNA restriction enzyme analysis. Provides a number of hits per enzyme and a list of non-cutters. Allows for selection of the enzymes and parameters.
Silent mutation restriction enzyme scan. Finds new restriction sites to insert (mutate) with no translation change.
Determines the number and highlights a rare E. coli codons in a provided DNA sequence. Maintained by UCLA, USA.
Provides graphical and numerical representation of the codon adaptation index, frequency distribution and GC content of the DNA sequence. Maintained by the GenScript, USA.
Multiple sequence alignment based phylogenetic tree prediction program.
EBI server for multiple sequence alignment on the web
Tool that uses split decomposition method to analyze and visualize distance data from biological sequences.
Multiple sequence alignment server and whole genome alignment database.
A multiple-sequence alignment program that also includes distance matrix methods for inferring trees.
Tree generation from distance data. [Results by email]

The SWISS-PROT database contains high-quality annotation, is non-redundant and cross-referenced to many other databases. SWISS-PROT is accompanied by TrEMBL, a computer-annotated supplement, which contains the translations of all coding sequences (CDS) present in the EMBL Nucleotide Sequence Database, which are not yet integrated into SWISS-PROT.

An experimental bioinformatics server. Classifies protein sequences as homodimers or non-homodimers. Applications: metabolic reconstruction, protein structure and function assignment, and drug-design.
PIR is a non-redundant annotated protein sequence database, and analytical tools, maintained by collaboration of MIPS, in Munich and the Japanese International Protein Sequence Database (JIPID).

column3: InterPro - The Integrated Resource of Protein Domains and Functional Sites.
column4: A database built from Pfam, PRINTS and PROSITE.

column3: Munich Information Center for Protein Sequences (MIPS)
column4: Bioinformatics research group offering organism specific information (Yeast, Cress) as well as search tools for public databases.
Provides automatic hierarchical classification of proteins sequences.

Includes WebOligoMelt (Annealing temperature of oligonucleotides), Virtual Ribosome (translate nucleotide sequences into peptides), and SeqScanGraph (graph melting temperature along nucleotide chain).
Ab initio predictions of protein function from protein sequence. The method works by integrating various predicted post-translational and localizational aspects of the proteins submitted.
Combines sequence and structural information for predicting the structure and/or function of your protein sequence, and can detect remote homologies beyond PSI-Blast.
3D protein structure prediction from amino acid sequence. Includes MEMSAT for transmembrane topology prediction, GenTHREADER and mGenTHREADER for fold recognition.
Secondary protein structure prediction from amino acid sequence; based on a consensus from several methods including DSC, PHD, NNSSP, PREDATOR, ZPRED, and MULPRED.
Open source Java implementation of the dynamic programming algorithm Smith-Waterman for biological local pairwise sequence alignment.
Automated comparative protein modelling server to make protein modelling accessible to biochemists and molecular biologists worldwide - from GlaxoWellcome Experimental Research, Geneva, Switzerland.
Online software for protein analysis from the Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics (SIB).
Powerful, state-of-the-art, 2-D analysis software package with user-friendly interface from the Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics.

UniProt (Universal Protein Resource) is a catalog of information on proteins. It is a central repository of protein sequence and function created by joining the information contained in Swiss-Prot, TrEMBL, and PIR.
Network service for comparing protein structures in 3D.
Identifies functionally important regions on the surface of a protein or domain, of known three-dimensional (3D) structure using the phylogenetic relations between close sequence homologues.

Service for detecting the multiple structural alignments of proteins. Uses the common geometrical cores between the input molecules. Does not require that all the input molecules participate in the alignment.

ESyPred3D is an automated homology modeling program getting benefit of the increased alignment performances of a new alignment strategy using neural networks. The final three dimensional structure is built using the modeling package MODELLER.
Accepts a single query protein sequence and returns the most probable Gene Ontology functional annotations in each of the three ontologies.

Predicts functional sites (linear motifs) in proteins, such as post-translational modification sites, ligand motifs, and targeting signals. Context-based rules and logical filters are applied to improve predictions.
Phyre is a free for academics service for predicting the 3-dimensional structure of a protein amino acid sequence.
Service to aid visualisation of potential errors in protein structures. Free for academic users.
Provides interactive service for matching protein structures in 3D and looking for structural homologues in PDB and SCOP databases, as well as in user-uploaded sets of structures.
A compilation of transcriptional regulatory protein factors and their cognate gene promoter elements along with DNA sequence search and analysis programs - from GBF, Braunschweig, Germany.

A database of annotated comparative protein structure models. The database includes fold assignments and alignments as well as information about putative ligand binding sites, SNP annotation, and protein-protein interactions.
Computational tool for sequence based prediction of intrinsic protein disorder and unstructured regions within a protein.
Public web service for the alignment and superposition of protein structures and the instant visualization of structural similarities.

column3: The ProCKSI Server: Protein Comparison, Knowledge, Similarity and Information
column4: ProCKSI is a decision support system for protein structure comparison. It provides tools for visualising, analysing, clustering and comparing results.
Method for finding 3-D similarities in protein structures from the UCSD Supercomputer Center.
Calculator with graphical user interface written in Qt library.
Tool to organize and analyze BLAST protein-data. It's free to use for scientific purpose.
Integrated resource, which provides information about ligands, sequence and structure motifs, their relative position and the neighbour environment.
Resource for the prediction of antigenicity combined with functional analysis of the target protein.
An online service for predicting MHC binding regions in antigens. It also offers the proteasomal and immunoproteasomal filters to improve the applicability of results.
Scansite searches for motifs within proteins that are likely to be phosphorylated by specific protein kinases or bind to domains such as SH2 domains, 14-3-3 domains or PDZ domains.
Lars Juhl Jensen's blog on computational biology. It features unpublished analyses, commentaries on peer-reviewed research, and live coverage from conferences.
Blog with lessons, tutorials, information and resources.
Molecular database technologies. To-Oracle database conversions. Data-mining and eCommerce development for genomics and proteomics.
Mascot, the on-line search engine for protein identification using mass spectrometry data
Hitachi Genetic Systems, by MiraiBio Inc, offers quality instruments, software, consumables and supporting applications for the genetics/molecular biology laboratory.
Specializes in epitope prediction and protein analysis for proteomics, diagnostics, therapeutics, life science research, and antibody production.
Develops and markets platforms, tools and products that accelerate post-genomic research, the advanced study of proteins and protein pathways, and drug target discovery.
Produces DNA secondary structure prediction software including alignments and Chous-Fasman analysis.

Global provider of workflow driven automation tools, knowledge management software, implementation services, and consulting to leading discovery-oriented, high throughput screening, genomics, proteomics, pharmaceuticals, and combinatorial chemistry companies.

Offers human and animal cell lines, media, reagents, and test kits from San Diego, CA.

Manufacture of sera, reagents for tissue culture, biotechnology, cell culture and blood products. Includes areas of OEM consulting and contract development, and catalog of standard sera available from Woodford, CA.

Develop assays for detection of apoptosis and cellular functions using cell permeable reagents. INcludes technical support and ordering from Mountain View, California.

Supplier of cell culture reagents for serum-free cell culture of primary cells, including stem cells, with specialty in bovine pituitary extract sourced from US or New Zealand. Located in Healdsburg, California.
Manufacturer of Class I, II, and III medical devices and blood plasma components for use in biotechnology, research and biomedical laboratory diagnostics. Located at Rancho Dominguez, California.

Offer reagents and services to develop and produce biopharmaceuticals, using mammalian and insect cell culture methods. Includes contacts for international subsidiaries, headquartered from Lenexa, Kansas.

FAQ and support in manufacturing processes, container types, dissociation, antibiotics, supplementation, cryopreservation and viability, in promoting Cellgro products from Herndon, Virginia.
Details of Mexican fetal bovine serum, from supplier in San Diego, California.
Products for the isolation of mammalian and non-mammalian cells, subcellular membranes, cell organelles, viruses and macromolecules using centrifugation techniques.

Developerer of hyaluranon hydrogels for 3D cell culture, stem cell culture, tissue engineering scaffolds and cell therapy.
Develops and markets the human and animal cells, optimized cell culture media and reagents for cell culture research.
FDA-registered manufacturer of sera, media and reagents for cell culture including human and animal blood products, custom media, supplements and reagents.
Distributor of a range of life science products for genomic analysis, cellular analysis, post-translational modification, signal transduction, drug discovery and cancer and immunology research.

Serum free media, specifically for fibroblasts, lymphocytes, epithelial, muscle, HeLa and tumor cells. Includes contacts for Asian distributors, European subsidiaries and profile of manufacturer headquartered in Pasching, Austria.

Provides essential research reagents to the scientific community by establishing, verifying, maintaining and distributing cell cultures and DNA derived from cell cultures. Held at the Institute for Medical Research, Camden, NJ, USA.
Offers molecular biology, such as operon oligonucleotide synthesis and plasmid purification, and cell culture supplies and liquid nitrogen storage for cell lines and biologicals.

A companion to cell. Abstracts available online.
Online version of the Journal of Cell Biology (Rockefeller University Press).
The official Journal of the Histochemical Society. Papers that report the development of new histochemical and cytochemical methods.
Articles concerning the molecular aspects of cell structure and function. Published by the American Society for Cell Biology (ASCB).
An authoritative source of fundamental knowledge and new developments in all aspects of the molecular biology of eukaryotic cells.
Clinical and diagnostic cytology and applied cell research and its methodology.
Original studies that address any aspect of the molecular biology of cell growth and differentiation, particularly as it relates to oncogenesis.
Reviews and Perspectives articles on a broad range of topics in the combined fields of Molecular Biology and Cell Biology.

Articles and site in Japanese, with access to TOC and abstracts in English.

Basic and applied research on cellular stress responses of animals, microorganisms and plants.

Research articles in all basic areas of connective tissue and matrix biology.

Covers all aspects of receptor-based cell recognition and signaling: understanding of the molecular basis of cell behavior as influenced by the interaction of cells with one another and with the extracellular environment including extracellular matrix, cytokines and chemotactic factors.

Covers all aspects of original research on receptors and ion channels and the related signalling elements, at the levels of molecular biology and genetics, biochemistry, physical analysis, molecular modelling, immunochemistry, molecular pharmacology and electrophysiology.
Multidisciplinary biomedical journal on endothelial cell research, dedicated to the rapid turnaround of significant basic and clinical research on the endothelium.
Experimental and theoretical work on the physics, chemistry, and biology of membranes at the molecular and cellular levels.
Monthly journal publishing original research that utilizes molecular techniques in the study of specific diseases.
Articles concerned with the immunological activities of cells in experimental or clinical situations.
Structural analysis of living material at every level of organization by all methods: light microscopy including confocal microscopy, electron microscopy, NMR, X-ray diffraction.
